Business

Kohl's gives long-vacant merchandising job to ex-Starbucks exec Michelle Gass





June 11, 2015


16 Comments



SHARE



















Michelle GassMilwaukee Journal Sentinel




By Rick Romell of the Journal Sentinel

June 11, 2015


16















Michelle Gass, the former Starbucks executive who came to Kohl's Corp. two years ago amid a wave of organizational change, has been named chief merchandising officer at the big retailer.The appointment fills a critical post at Kohl's, one that has stood vacant for 14 months. It also solidifies Gass' standing as a prime candidate to one day succeed Kevin Mansell as CEO of the $19 billion company, which employs thousands of people at its Menomonee Falls headquarters."It's a good move," analyst Patrick McKeever of MKM Partners said. "I've been pretty impressed by Michelle since she joined the company. She's a rising star and I think it makes sense."In an email, Mark Altschwager of Robert W. Baird & Co. said he too has been "impressed by the leadership and energy" Gass has brought to Kohl's. The move increases the odds that she will ultimately succeed Mansell, Altschwager said.Kohl's also said Thursday that it has begun an external search for a chief operating officer — a new position for the firm. Whomever is chosen for that role also likely will be an eventual CEO candidate.Many observers had expected Kohl's to announce a new chief merchant months ago. But the decision to go with Gass emerged as the company began embarking on a sweeping series of initiatives it calls the "greatness agenda," Mansell said in an interview.Gass, who has been credited with playing a key role in Starbucks' turnaround of a few years ago, joined Kohl's in June 2013 as the firm was working to rebound from mediocre sales performance and operational missteps.Named chief customer officer, she has overseen e-commerce, marketing and efforts to more fully engage consumers through such measures as a loyalty rewards program that has attracted some 30 million members.As Kohl's searched for a new chief merchant — the executive who oversees the planning, development and allocation of the apparel, home goods and other products sold in the chain's 1,164 department stores and online business — Mansell increasingly saw that role as tightly connected to the work Gass was already spearheading."It became more clear everyday that these two things, customer engagement and product, are linked completely," he said.That pointed toward Gass as a logical person to head up merchandising, and Mansell began seriously weighing that option as long as a year ago. But given Gass' relatively thin experience with department-store retailing, Mansell wanted to make sure she was ready."Michelle has been new to our industry and our sector, so there was a learning curve," Mansell said. Actually, she's not entirely new to the industry. Just before joining Kohl's, she spent four and a half years on the board of Ann Inc., operator of more than 1,000 women's apparel stores under the Ann Taylor and Loft brands.And running Kohl's e-commerce operations for two years has given Gass in-depth knowledge of Kohl's products and supply structure, Mansell said."She's ready for this," he said. "She is more than ready."With comparable-store sales growing the last two quarters after five straight quarters of year-over-year declines, it should be clear that Gass is "making a big difference," Mansell said.Altschwager noted Gass' lack of extensive merchandising experience before joining Kohl's. But he said that with the company's large team of merchandise management and product development executives, "the chief merchant role is more about leadership and strategic direction than having an eye for fashion trends."Gass' new title will be chief merchandising and customer officer. She will retain most of her previous responsibilities, with Mansell taking over digital and e-commerce strategies and operations until a chief operating officer is found.Besides digital technology and e-commerce, the chief operating officer will oversee Kohl's store operations, supply chain and logistics. Like every legacy retailer, Kohl's is looking for the most effective way to appeal to consumers who increasingly tote smartphones and combine online shopping with the traditional brick-and-mortar variety. Placing the same person in charge of both digital and physical-store operations will speed Kohl's progress along that path, Mansell said."It's a different way to structure, but I think it's the future for us," he said.In the merchandising role, Gass replaces Donald Brennan, who resigned in March 2014. He had received a relatively low performance rating for the previous year.Mansell, who is 62 and has been CEO since August 2008, has no plans to retire. But he said that as Kohl's chief executive and chairman of its board of directors, he wants the board to have choices in succession planning."And I want enough time...to evaluate the performance of specific executives," he said.




